TY  - JOUR
T1  - Spatial Competition with Heterogeneous Firms
AU  - Vogel, Jonathan
Y1  - 2008/06/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/589891
DO  - 10.1086/589891
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 423
EP  - 466
VL  - 116
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - I model endogenous horizontal and vertical product differentiation with arbitrarily many heterogeneous firms. Firms are asymmetric in that they differ in their marginal costs. I prove that under an equilibrium refinement, all economically relevant firm outcomes are uniquely determined across all strict subgame perfect Nash equilibria. There are two central results. First, a firm?s price, market share, and profit are independent of its neighbors? marginal costs, conditional on the average marginal cost in the market. Second, more productive firms are more isolated, all else equal. In particular, the distance between two firms is strictly decreasing in their average marginal cost.
AB  - I model endogenous horizontal and vertical product differentiation with arbitrarily many heterogeneous firms. Firms are asymmetric in that they differ in their marginal costs. I prove that under an equilibrium refinement, all economically relevant firm outcomes are uniquely determined across all strict subgame perfect Nash equilibria. There are two central results. First, a firm?s price, market share, and profit are independent of its neighbors? marginal costs, conditional on the average marginal cost in the market. Second, more productive firms are more isolated, all else equal. In particular, the distance between two firms is strictly decreasing in their average marginal cost.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/589891
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/589891
Y2  - 2024/03/19
